This can be due to the fact that MnO2 can oxidise H2O2, in the presence of moderate acidic medium (as in our instance), whereas MnO2 cannot oxidise Cl- (HCl) in the presence of mild acidic medium. The intramolecular redox reaction of MnO2 in the presence of H2SO4 is also only possible in very acidic medium in the case of H2SO4, and this process is kinetically unfavorable due to the large energy of activation. As a result, the intensity of the PL turn-on in the presence of HCl and H2SO4 is relatively low and practically identical to the intensity of the quenched probe (Fig. 7). The detailed reaction mechanism is discussed below;
MnO2+4H+ + 2e-→ Mn2+ + 2H2O, E
